properties.program_name: Delaware River Watershed Protection Fund - Forestland Capital Grants
properties.organization: The Land Conservancy of New Jersey
properties.description: This project is located in the NJ Highlands Cluster within the Paulins Kill focus area. Paulins Kill is the largest Phase II focus area. Within this focus area, the Cluster has targeted 850 acres in Bobcat Alley for land protection. Stressors include forestland conversion, lack of forest stewardship, and inconsistent use of Best Management Practices in land management, which have resulted in mid- to high-range total suspended solids and total phosphorus, high water temperatures, and loss of natural riparian habitat in some sections of the river. Conserving the unprotected uplands and headwater forests will keep water temperatures and nutrient and sediment loads at low levels. The preservation of this property will preserve unprotected headwaters and upland forests approximately 315 feet upgrade from the same unnamed tributary to the Paulins Kill that runs through our Phase I Yards Creek project.  This acquisition will preserve 28 acres in Bobcat Alley and is the second phase in a series of acquisitions surrounding Yards Creek and the Yards Creek reservoirs. Combined with Phase I of the project, this will make a grand total of 154 acres preserved in Bobcat Alley as a result of our new Yards Creek Preserve. This project builds on past and ongoing work in the DRWI by preventing in-fill development and the impacts of suburban encroachment on forested lands.  The Land Conservancy is under contract with the landowner and is expected to preserve the property in fall of 2019.

properties.program_name: Delaware River Watershed Protection Fund - Farm Buffer Capital Grants
properties.description:
The Subject property consists of 26 acres of contiguous woodlands and a small wooded stream correct which protrudes into the Match property. It is adjacent to the recently conserved 16 Years LLC property, which contains the headwaters to two tributaries to the French and Pickering Creeks. The water flows into Bryn Coed Preserve, which has been conserved by Natural Lands. This property provides a buffer to nearly 2,000 acres of conserved lands and was proposed for a 20 lot subdivision by the previous owner. The protection of the land will maintain the High Quality status of the groundwater and decrease the storm water that the high-density proposed development would generate. 
There is no development on the property despite the metrics showing 0.22 acres of developed land.

properties.organization: The Land Conservancy of New Jersey
properties.description: The project is located in the New Jersey Highlands Cluster, Upper Musconetcong Focus Area.  The Upper Musconetcong focus area targeted 600 acres for land protection of high quality streams and tributaries to the main stem of the Musconetcong River.  The upstream areas have consistently high water quality indicators and preservation of these lands will help prevent degradation of water quality in the headwaters.   The project site is located in the headwaters of Weldon Brook, a FW2-Trout Production stream. Preservation of the property will contribute to protect water quality measures in the watershed.  Two tributaries meander throughout the project site, with emergent and forested wetlands filtering out the sediments, and contribute to the high water quality of Weldon Brook.  Preservation of the 25 acre property in fee is in support of the focus area goals.  In addition, the Highlands Trail traverses the parcel, and preservation of the property will secure and buffer the trail.  The property will be acquired in fee by The Land Conservancy of New Jersey (TLC-NJ) and the Morris County Park Commission (MCPC). The MCPC will own and manage the land as an addition to Mahlon Dickerson Reservation, and the Highlands Trail will be maintained by the New York New Jersey Trail Conference.  The GIS map layer erroneously indicates this site as preserved.

properties.practice_name: Culvers Brook Preserve - Reforested Area (to >=90% natural)
properties.program_name: Delaware River Watershed Protection Fund - Forestland Capital Grants
properties.description:
The WRWMG plans to use its extensive watershed restoration and stewardship experience and work in partnership with the GCLWF to reforest the headwater areas on the 1st and 2nd order tributaries running through the retired course. This will include planting of 100 wide riparian forested buffers along the eastern shore of the pond and both sides of the ponds inlet and outlet streams. Additional buffer plantings will performed over time to further close in the open fairway areas. All of these buffer plantings will include a diverse mixture of native containerized trees and shrubs, be installed at a density of 300 stems/acre, and protected with a 5-foot-tall ventilated shelter and support stake. The plantings shall be accomplished by hand tools utilizing volunteers during education and outreach events organized and facilitated by the WRWMG in partnership with the GCLWCF. 
Loading reductions per year calculated in FD are TSS 303.13 lbs per year; nitrogen 8.82 lbs per year;  phosphorus .71 lbs  per year.

properties.description: This project is within the Cherry Valley Focus Area of the Poconos-Kittatinny Cluster (PKC).  Land protection is an approved strategy for this cluster. The Mountain Run project will add to contiguous protected lands. It builds upon four other protection projects completed in this Focus Area with DRWI, plus two projects, same Focus Area, that were completed without DRWI funds.  Mountain Run goes through a small portion of the property; the rest of the property drains to Cherry Creek, a High-Quality tributary of the Delaware River. The Nature Conservancy will purchase fee simple interest and transfer it to U.S. Fish & Wildlife Service (USFWS) to addition to the Cherry Valley National Wildlife Refuge.
